{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":159549,"duration_api_ms":170310,"num_turns":18,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"87e0125a-94ef-493b-a853-decc96564a75","total_cost_usd":0.6706787499999999,"usage":{"input_tokens":757,"cache_creation_input_tokens":34308,"cache_read_input_tokens":501741,"output_tokens":4915,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":34308,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":75,"outputTokens":3925,"cacheReadInputTokens":350295,"cacheCreationInputTokens":19195,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.07872325000000001,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000},"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":757,"outputTokens":4915,"cacheReadInputTokens":501741,"cacheCreationInputTokens":34308,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.5919555,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"All three amendments are well-grounded in verified code analysis. Amendment fr-18-e23d3048 identifies a genuine bug: the `?` at engine.rs:4649 propagates snapshot write failures through the `?` chain at lines 3307→950/1537, completely bypassing `fail_run_result`, which leaves run.json in Running state while the journal has a stage_failed event — an inconsistency the code comments explicitly warn against. Amendment fr-18-86b3413e correctly calls for test coverage of this behavioral change, with existing test infrastructure (FailingSnapshotWrite) available. Amendment fr-18-4d7180f4 correctly identifies that the deterministic hash-mixing of `subsec_nanos()` cannot diverge same-tick calls, contradicting the code's own comments.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-18-86b3413e","decision":"accept","rationale":"The behavioral change from log-and-swallow to mandatory `?` propagation at line 4649 is significant and untested. The FailingSnapshotWrite fixture already exists at conformance_spec/scenarios.rs:17922, making implementation straightforward. The proposed two-part verification — (a) engine returns error on snapshot write failure during backoff, and (b) derive_resume_state correctly reconstructs from journal alone — directly validates the journal-is-authoritative invariant that the retry-backoff path depends on. This test would also serve as a regression guard for the bug in fr-18-e23d3048, confirming that after a fix, the system handles snapshot write failures gracefully."},{"amendment_id":"fr-18-e23d3048","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified as a genuine bug by tracing the error propagation path. At engine.rs:4649, the `?` on write_run_snapshot propagates the error out of execute_stage_with_retry. At line 3307, the `.await?` propagates it out of execute_run_internal. At lines 950/1537, another `.await?` propagates it to the top-level caller. At no point in this chain is fail_run_result invoked — despite being used at ~60 other error sites in the same file. The result: the journal has a stage_failed event (durably appended before line 4649), but run.json remains in its prior Running state because the disk write failed and nothing else attempted to update it. This is exactly the journal/snapshot divergence the comments at lines 4643-4648 warn about. The fix should either catch the snapshot write error and route it through fail_run_result, or revert to the previous log-and-continue behavior since the journal is authoritative and a stale-but-consistent snapshot is recoverable."},{"amendment_id":"fr-18-4d7180f4","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified by reading retry_policy.rs. The apply_jitter function derives its entire entropy from SystemTime::now().subsec_nanos(). The Murmur-style hash mix (XOR-shift + wrapping_mul at lines 145-151) is purely deterministic: identical nanos input always produces identical mixed output. The comments at lines 142-144 claim the mixing prevents 'identical jitter for closely-spaced calls' on coarse-grained clocks, but this is mathematically impossible — a deterministic function cannot produce different outputs from identical inputs. On platforms with 1ms or 10ms clock resolution, concurrent retries within the same tick will compute the same jitter factor. A thread-local RNG, monotonic counter, or even mixing in the thread ID would genuinely solve same-tick correlation as the comments promise."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"492c2ede-0206-4536-a8b6-2f6d6c5198d9"}
